w Orleans, St. Louis, and Detroit survived the transition to American rule. French traders from Mid-America such as the Chouteaus and Robidouxs of St. Louis then became agents of change in the West, perfecting a strategy of "middle grounding" by pursuing alliances within Indian and Mexican communities in advance of American settlement and re-investing fur trade profits in land, town sites, banks, and transportation. The Bourgeois Frontier provides the missing French connection between the urban Midwest and western expansion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aFrench AmericansxHistoryxWest (U.S.). 0aFrench AmericanszWest (U.S.)xHistory. 0aFrenchxHistoryxWest (U.S.). 0aFrenchzWest (U.S.)xHistory. 0aFrontier and pioneer lifexWest (U.S.). 0aFrontier and pioneer lifezWest (U.S.) 0aFrontier and pioneer lifezWest (U.S.). 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300155761423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300155761.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles